comments.body:
There are no identifiable duplicates in the resource record, or in the Top Container view. 
![Screenshot (56)](https://github.com/pulibrary/aspace_helpers/assets/75688375/3b548d54-35b8-42ee-b7d9-3c2531df7525)
![Screenshot (57)](https://github.com/pulibrary/aspace_helpers/assets/75688375/95f93943-1c14-41b4-a7a7-40c4c840876b)

Here is what happens with running the folder labels transformation scenario: 
![Screenshot (58)](https://github.com/pulibrary/aspace_helpers/assets/75688375/f45b5690-67d8-40f6-aa93-1c2f3a795d45)

It looks like the XML for the second set of accidentally imported archival objects is repeated in the file: 
![Screenshot (59)](https://github.com/pulibrary/aspace_helpers/assets/75688375/68e56148-bcd2-465e-89b8-f3f5669016df)

If you look at [Subseries 1C](https://aspace.princeton.edu/staff/resources/3755#tree::archival_object_1479557), the two duplicate series are there at the end. 

Can you simply delete them from there? If the situation is more complex, let me know and I'll help!
Wow, I totally missed that they nested there! Thank you for being so thorough, Regine!!!!!!!! It works now
Thank you for providing all the background information--that helped a lot!!

comments.body: @faithc Yup, do you have one where there's no top-level note and one below is marked something?

I don't think that use case should exist anymore. Any collection that includes a restriction or materials that need review should now have the "review" value at the collection level. Collections with no value type at the collection level should all be totally open. Does that make sense?
